Chicago Ridehail Open Data: Drivers

Data source

Chicago publishes three data sets about Transportation Network Providers operations in the city. This notebook uses the Drivers data set. All three are updated monthly. I download the Drivers set as a CSV file; the Trips data set is too big for that, and (in other notebooks) I query it from the notebook.

After download, remove some obvious gaps and errors (like drivers with a start date before 2011, or drivers with a start date after the month reported).

In this notebook, “drivers” = “active drivers”, which is to say drivers with a number of trips > 0 in a given month.

Trips per month

Start with an overview of trip volume over time.

Discussion

There are three periods:

  1. Expansion until about 9M trips per month at the beginning of 2018
  2. Flatlining at 9M trips per day during 2018 and 2019
  3. Covid-driven collapse in early 2020 followed by steady recovery during 2021, so in mid-2022 the number of trips is back to about 2/3 of pre-Covid levels.

For comparison with other cities, 9M trips per month is equivalent to: - 300,000 per day, or - 12000 per hour, or - 200 per minute.

Driver population

The trend for active drivers parallels that for trips.

The trends for all drivers (including those with no trips) have some similarities and differences to the trips:

  1. Expansion until early 2017.
  2. During the first half of 2017 the number of drivers falls off and levels out at about 70K. This is while the number of trips is still increasing.
  3. Flatlining during 2017-H2, 2018, 2019.
  4. A slower and less complete Covid-driven drop-off of drivers during 2020 than trips, followed by some recovery during 2021.

Trips and drivers are now back to about 0.6 of the pre-Covid numbers.

Regarding the outliers in Q2 2018, there is a note on the City of Chicago web site:

[S]ome vehicle records for Q2 2018 (April-June) were reported for the quarter as a whole, rather than for individual months. For purposes of this dataset, those records have been assigned to 2018-06 (June). Therefore, some caution in interpreting this month and the quarter as a whole is advised.

Discussion

The basic pattern is the same as that for trips. The Covid plummet is a bit less complete, although still dramatic.

Drivers, by hours driven

There is no one Uber driver. To understand how Uber operates, it helps to know what the range of driver participation is. Some drive only occasionally, some drive full time.

Categorizing drivers

The Chicago data set does not provide driver times on the platform. The nearest we get is the number of trips in the month.

Using an average of 20 minutes per trip (from the Trips data set) and a utilization rate of 66% (a generous estimate from Fehr & Peers) gives two trips per hour. A 30 hour week translates into 60 trips, which is about 250 trips per month.

Any attempt to divide the distribution into categories is a bit arbitrary, but this section shows a few categorization schemes.

Seattle classification

First, The Seattle classification of Hyman et al to map that onto the Chicago data. The categories are:

Category Trips Estimated hours / week
1 < 40 < 5
2 41 – 160 5 – 20
3 161 – 240 20 – 30
4 241 – 320 30 – 40
5 > 320 > 40

The proportion of Casual drivers fell off quickly from 2016 to 2018, and the number of part-time (160-240) and full-time drivers rose. Since then, the composition has changed only a little.

Discussion

Despite the changes over the last five years, including the maturing of the Uber platform and Covid, the driver population has remained surprisingly consistent. Full time drivers (over 275 trips per month) make up only about one in six drivers, but deliver over 40% of all trips.

Full-timers and part-timers are both essential to Uber and Lyft’s ability to deliver the volume of trips they handle. But these two groups do not always share the same interests.

Mean and median number of trips per driver

Although there is no “one type of Uber driver”, averages may still be useful to track trends.

The average number of trips per driver increased during 2017 (as measured both by median and mean): the number of drivers stayed roughly the same while the number of trips continued to grow. In 2018 and 2019 there was a roughly steady state, with an average of about 125 trips per month (about 16 hours per week), a number that has been restored during 2022.

Driver longevity and churn

Driver population by longevity

The first chart takes a specific month and shows the distribution of drivers, by longevity, on the platform in that month.

It can be easier to interpret this if we lump drivers into new or long-term workers, based on whether they have been on the platform for more or less than a year.

Both mean and median longevity (below) confirm the observation that the driver population has been on the platform for longer, over time, albeit with a major Covid interruption.

The Chicago data does not allow us to see whether drivers have gaps in their work: we just have a first month they are recognized and the reporting month.

The typical driver has now been on the platform for almost a year. Drivers who drive more trips have, on average, been on the platform just a little longer.
